  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1777899254" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1777899254" />
    <a title="Petrik" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59458347-petrik"><img alt="Petrik" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1568016775p2/59458347.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1777899254?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Petrik" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Petrik" href="/user/show/59458347-petrik">Petrik</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781984819376" href="/book/show/43069501-red-rising">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Sci-fi &amp; Dystopian fans</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1777899254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10072876100412778560"><b>4.5/5 Stars</b> <br/><br/>Buddy reading this with my favorites:<br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/ravageroftomes' rel='nofollow noopener'>Sweet Mary</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/La_Luna_Moonchild' rel='nofollow noopener'>Sister Sarah</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/35431290-tweebs' rel='nofollow noopener'>Tweebie</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/35147071-jenn-the-dark-lord-scribe-house-of-slytheread' rel='nofollow noopener'>Jennymort</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/may-flower' rel='nofollow noopener'>Innocent May</a><br/><br/>Let’s get the two most asked questions about this book out of the way first.<br/> <br/><b>1.	Is this book geared towards YA audience?</b><br/>No, it’s not. The only thing in this book that fits the YA genre is that Darrow’s (The MC) age starts at 16 years old in the beginning, that’s it. Everything else; the writing, plot, themes, and world-building, in my opinion, belongs in the adult territory.<br/><br/><b>2.	Is this book </b></span>
  <span id="freeText10072876100412778560" style="display:none"><b>4.5/5 Stars</b> <br><br>Buddy reading this with my favorites:<br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/ravageroftomes" rel="nofollow noopener">Sweet Mary</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/La_Luna_Moonchild" rel="nofollow noopener">Sister Sarah</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/35431290-tweebs" rel="nofollow noopener">Tweebie</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/35147071-jenn-the-dark-lord-scribe-house-of-slytheread" rel="nofollow noopener">Jennymort</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/may-flower" rel="nofollow noopener">Innocent May</a><br><br>Let’s get the two most asked questions about this book out of the way first.<br> <br><b>1.	Is this book geared towards YA audience?</b><br>No, it’s not. The only thing in this book that fits the YA genre is that Darrow’s (The MC) age starts at 16 years old in the beginning, that’s it. Everything else; the writing, plot, themes, and world-building, in my opinion, belongs in the adult territory.<br><br><b>2.	Is this book really similar to <i>The Hunger Games</i>?</b><br>Honestly, there were a few similarities, especially during the competition. The right question though would have to be <i>“are they in the same league with each other?”</i> My answer will have to be <b>absolutely not.</b><br><br><b>I personally think that putting <i>The Hunger Games</i> in the same league with <i>Red Rising</i> is a disservice to this book.</b> <i>Red Rising</i> made the <i>The Hunger Games</i> looked like child's play; I’m not going to bash <i>The Hunger Games</i> but in my opinion that series is so over-hyped, oh wait I just did. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1483758691i/21646603._SY540_.jpg" width="”400”/" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Okay I know that image didn’t happen in the book otherwise Katniss would become Voldemort but I think that Darrow is a better protagonist in every aspect compared to her. Enough about the comparison though, I’ll get on with my review now.<br><br>The tale is told from Darrow’s 1st person narrative and it tells the story of how he’s trying to achieve revenge for the events that happened to him at the beginning of the book. Rage, politics, love, vengeance, sadness, hierarchy, racism, and slavery were heavily evident in the book. I’ll say this once again, this book is not specifically for YA audience; there were rape and hints of cannibalism that I don’t think is suitable for a younger audience. Maybe an adult sci-fi that’s also accessible to some teenager sounds more appropriate than labeling it as YA.<br><br>The characters in this book were incredibly easy to get attached to. It’s only the first installment in the series and yet I can’t help myself but truly empathize with them since the first 70 pages. It’s difficult for me to like a sci-fi/dystopian series that’s done from the first-person perspective because almost every YA Sci-Fi/Dystopian books or movies I’ve read or watched consisted of angsty whiny teenager who always went <i>“wah wah wah I’m a monster wah wah ohhh two guys like me what to do what to do wahhh wahh”</i> shut up, buy some Pizza and stuff them in your mouth for god sake.<br><br>Darrow as an MC isn’t any of those things. He’s a complex character filled with rage and, at the same time, full of love for his people and friends. He’s not afraid to get things done when needed and he does not fall in despair; he never stops trying to shape his own future by finding the strength to fight for what he believed in.<br><br><b>
  <i>
    <blockquote>“The measure of a man is what he does when he has power.”</blockquote>
  </i>
</b><br><br>Conflicted with his main mission and love for his new friends, I’m excited to see how his character will develop further and see the progress of his relationships with the other fantastic side characters; Eo, Mustang, Cassius, Dancer, Mickey, Roque, Pax, and my favorite—probably everyone too—character: Sevro.<br><br><b>Picture: <i>Sevro</i> by Justin Wong</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1483758691i/21646604._SY540_.jpg" width="400" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>None of the things I mentioned above would’ve made the book worked for me without Pierce Brown’s engaging writing style. I absolutely loved his prose; easy to follow and the pacing was bloody relentless. The book felt naturally fast-paced, utterly readable, and the words he chose were raw, full of rage, brutal and also poignant at times. <b>Almost every scene, whether it was superb actions, strategic planning, or even when the characters were just talking with each other pumped my blood with adrenaline rush.</b> Words like hatred, vengeance, justice, rage were often used that reading the book reminded me of Kratos from the <i>God of War</i> video game series.<br><br>The only minor problems I had with <i>Red Rising</i> was the world-building aspect. Don’t get me wrong, the world-building was great and Pierce Brown managed to create a truly atmospheric world. However, the area where the competition took place feels like Earth even though the setting is on Mars. I also think that some of the terminologies would’ve benefited from additional detail. There were many unique terms and devices mentioned that weren’t explained clearly; it’s up to the reader to fit in the pieces with their imagination and this can take a bit of time to get used to. <br><br><b>There’s a super high chance that this series will go down as one of my favorite series of all time depending on the sequels.</b> <i>Red Rising</i> was already fantastic to me and I truly enjoyed reading it. However, everyone who’ve read and loved the series told and reminded me that the sequels were superior which bloodydamn excites me. Without the minor problems I mentioned, this book would’ve been a 5 stars read. I highly recommend this series to anyone who’s looking for a great sci-fi dystopian story that’s not plagued by any infuriating YA tropes. Filled with an amazing plot, brutal actions, well-paced storyline, fantastic characterizations, and believable development; <i>Red Rising</i> was a fantastic start to a sci-fi series and I immensely enjoyed it.<br><br><b>You can order the book from: <u><a href="http://www.bookdepository.com/book/9780345539786/?a_aid=petrikleo" rel="nofollow noopener">Book Depository (Free shipping)</a></u></b><br><br><i>You can find the rest of my reviews at <b><u><a href="http://novelnotions.net" rel="nofollow noopener">Novel Notions</a></u></b></i></span>
  <a data-text-id="10072876100412778560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


